Mr. Kelley is in training for the Boston Marathon -- his

Mr. Kelley is such an institution that Hopkinton, Mass., where the race begins, has made him an honorary citizen.
Recalls Suni Tomomitsu, one of the runners: "At first we thought, 'Oh, wow, he's like Mafia man.'
Then we said, 'Oh no, this is nice Johnny Kelley.'
"That's not a prediction, just a goal," he says.
Then, in 1933, he finished 37th in a field of about 200 runners.
(He has competed, all told, in 112 marathons, including the 1936 and 1948 Olympics.
